segments.text: And the impact of that.
Also, we were building out here, which is a whole new area, and there weren't builders and workmen and so forth in the area.
So we went all through that in, let's say, the end of 73, most, I mean, end of 72, all 73.
We opened in October of 74.
And about that time, it just went nosedive again.
And then we cut away back in 75.
76 residential sales start picking up a little bit.
Things start getting a little better in 77.
Then they really start going up like this and really starting looking fantastic about 79 and 80 and 81 and 82 and then going right down again.
Now we're just kind of going up again on the scale because we're hearing of more deals.
People are looking for large hunks of space.
People are looking around, thinking of doing buildings.
So we see things happening, and things are getting better.
We're going to remodel this building over here, which was the Superior Oil building until Mobil bought them out.
Mobil bought them out and cleaned out the company.
We got the building back, so we're going to remodel that building and try to put that back on the market.
We've got the whole building is empty, 80,000 feet.
So we're going to remodel that.
We're remodeling the first floor lobby of the Bank One building.
So we're now doing several things.
We're planning for new commercial developments, shopping centers, malls, and so forth.
We're doing remodeling of existing buildings to upgrade the quality of those buildings, and then we're building some new buildings, both here and in
That all sounds kind of seat-of-the-pants.
Is it seat-of-the-pants, or do you employ market analysis firms or whatever to look around and give you suggestions and ideas?
Yeah, I'd say that, well, let's see, what would be an example?
If we were going to do an office building
We would do a market survey in terms of what are the demands for that kind of space to try to give an idea of what size building we should do.
And what we would then do is develop a budget based on that program, get the total project budget prepared.
Then we'd run a performa on the building to determine can we really, of course, a lot of them, once they see the pants, it's just using judgment based on
You know, your own knowledge or what you can get from consultants.
If we're going to do, let's say, we want to do another small village shopping center, we'll bring in a market consultant, for example.
He will then gather up all the data that we have from, say, Mel DePay, who does all our market research.
And he can then see how many people are living in that area right now
What's the potential for growth in that area based on our development plans and what the growth has been historically?
And then he could say, well, you can justify to build, let's say, 100,000 square feet here, but you need to have maybe 50,000 square feet this year, 75 this year, and then max out 100 at that year.
And if you do that, and if you have this kind of a store, and then you have these ancillary type of facilities here, I think it'll work.
We say, OK.
So we then go through the land plan to try to see if we can get a site, get the thing to work.
Then we will get cost estimates on that, as I say, do a budget, do a performa.
Let's say everything goes smoothly that way.
It doesn't always go that way.
Rarely ever goes that way.
proceed to go ahead and build it.
Is Hallmark doing the marketing for the mall?
Yeah, well, we've done it jointly with them.
But there, you're talking about a very long area, I mean, large area.
They go as far south as FM 1960 and go north to Conroe or even Huntsville.
It's a regional mall.
Now, that construction is actually destroyed on there?
No, no, no, no.
I wish it had.
Where are you?
We're on a standstill there.
Part of that is due to hard times, economy, and Sears store.
You see, Hallmark is part of Sears.
The intent was to bring Sears in as one of the first stores.
Sears is having financial problems.
They've been trying to get Sears in here.
We've been saying, look, we'd better let's drop Sears and let's try to bring in someone else.
So that's what we're trying to do right now.
We've got Dillard's committed to open.
We need to get another one to start the first phase of the development.
Yeah, because don't you anchor those things?
Yeah.
Oh, yeah.
The mall is designed to have, depending on how you want to count it, five or six anchors.
And it's designed so that we can do the top part of the mall starting with two anchors up here, two major department stores, which would be like Dillard's and Sears.
But, you know, we could go with Dillard's and maybe Foley's or Dillard's and maybe Penny's or, you know, something like that.
So we're in the process of trying to see if we can pin someone down and make a commitment to go in.
And where would that leave Hallmark, the management firm?
Oh, Hallmark.
Hobart is independent.
The development company is independent.
They can operate independently of Sears as a department store.
However, they're owned by the same company.
They say they're independent, but I notice that they seem to be pretty tied to try to get Sears in.
But we're saying, look, time's going by and we need to get this going.
And the thing is that the Houston economy, while it's improved, is still not, you know, isn't that
buoyant of an economy.
Greens Point Mall is our closest mall, and that's probably 10 miles from here south of us.
And it's kind of rocky right now.
Lord & Taylor, which is their quality store, has moved out.
And that's brought, I think, the level of quality of that center down.
I think the population in that area has shifted.
Oh, it has.
Sorry, it's this way over here.
Yeah, well, it's shifted in at the
Economic base of that area is lower.
So they're looking at that, and they're saying, well, look, if we build a store here, all the people in this area are going to go there.
They're not going to go down to our existing store down there, and the existing store is not doing that well, so why should we build another store up here?
Dealers will go in here because he doesn't have a store down there.
Yeah, he does.
Huh?
Is there a deal?
Oh, that's right.
They took over Joski's.
Yeah.
It's a smaller store.
That's right.
They took over Joski's, I think.
Is it Joski's?
No.
There is no Joski's down there.
No.
Who did they take over Joski's?
Huh?
Yeah, they took over Joski's.
Yeah.
I was looking at the Galleria where they... Yeah, there is a dealer.
It's at Green's Point, isn't there?
Yeah.
That's...
They took over another store.
It was Joski's.
I don't go there.
I think Galleria.
There was a Dillard's and a Joski's, wasn't it?
There was a Joski's there.
It was a separate freestanding store right across the street from the Galleria, right.
And Foley's, our anchor in colonization is Foley's and Dillard's.
Yes, right.
How's the enrollment at A&M?
Is it still going up?
Well, they've capped it.
Have they?
Yeah.
From what I hear in the Senate, they've got some enrollment management things that are working.
Which aren't working, but in terms of actual leading it, I don't know.
Anyway, we've got about $41,000.
Yeah, my daughter went to A&M.
Benching?
Yeah, through agriculture.
In what field was she?
She got her bachelor's in agriculture economics, and then she took her graduate degree also in agri-economics, but her major emphasis was in international trade.
So she's now with the Foreign Agriculture Service.
Travels all over the world.
That's exciting.
Represents the U.S. government and the rice market.
Oh, no kidding.
You have to read my book.
I have a long history of the American rice industry.
Really?
Yes, sir.
She would enjoy that.
How current is your book?
Last year?
Oh, I'd like to get a copy of that.
Yeah, in fact, she's delivering a speech in Kansas or someplace today.
That was an exciting project.
Really, yeah.
She knows everybody.
I mean, she knows all the rice people in Thailand.
But this woman is just going to be translated into Japanese?
Yeah, Japanese.
Well, her last trip, she went to Seoul, Tokyo.
Jakarta, Bangkok.
That's a fascinating world.
It goes way back, too.
Oh, it's real interesting.
I know.
It's real interesting.
I didn't know anything about it.
I mean, I grew up in the city.
I didn't know anything about agriculture.
A friend of mine, Clive Harston, who just retired from .
Did you know a Dr. Cook in agriculture?
Yeah.
Dr. Cook was her mentor.
In fact, she was interested in coming back here.
We were sidetracking.
And he's at University of Missouri.
And he was trying to encourage her to come.
What's going to happen?
Well, I think if the Houston economy can just keep picking up, even if it's gradual, I think that we're just on the threshold of doing our greatest work here in the woodlands.
I just see it just going like this.
prefer that the economy just creep up gradually and solid base, rather than this big spikes of boom and bust kind of thing.
And then we can develop very nicely.
And I think with the regional mall and what that would do to this whole area, the spin-off of developments around malls, have you seen up in Bryan College Station area or anywhere else?
We'll build office buildings around here.
That's why we're doing this plan here.
We're now talking about large office buildings.
I mean, we're really starting about going big time.
I just hope I can stay around to see it all happen.
Well, you know, that's what I've since been talking about.
Because I've suffered through this all these years, hanging out with my short fingernails.
Now I'd like to stay here and enjoy and see this tremendous, what I think should be really tremendous development.
I mean, we made an offer to buy that downtown site, to build that tower downtown Houston.
What's that?
Gottlieb called that super block.
Is that an internal kind of thing?
No, it's one block, downtown Houston, right across from Shell Plaza.
If you know where Shell is, Shell is right here.
Tenneco is here.
Two Shells here.
The old Bank of the Southwest is right here.
There's just a block right there.
Bank of Southwest owned the land.
They were going to build that Bank of Southwest Tower.
They had an architectural competition in the 80s.
And Murphy Yan, Helmut Yan, architect from Chicago, won the design competition.
And they were going to build that building.
They, in fact, tore down a 20-story building that was on the site for that building.
Well, again, they were ready to go ahead, and the economy went down, and they didn't do it.
And, of course, then Bank of Southwest merged into become M-Bank.
And, of course, later they went bankrupt.

m corp then became then they went bankrupt so we had offered to buy the site and we were well along i had i was working with helen young from chicago we were revising plans to come and do maybe about a 75-story office building it was a gigantic project that's the kind of project you get into and you'd be into it for four or five years we i had done the budgets and we were around
Last budget I did was around $400, $450 million to do that building.
Incredible projects.
I mean, they're so, you know, you get into things like, you know, the building's that tall, you know, with wind, they want to move like that.
Well, it's the first turn in time I've heard of a tuned mass damper.
It's like a huge block of concrete up there that's tuned so that when the building wants to go this way, this thing is moving that way, and vice versa, to
stop the building from swaying.
And then you get into the analysis of the elevators, the mechanical systems, and the security systems.
I mean, it's just like a little world into all of itself.
That building, when it moves, every piece of metal, and glass, and roof, and everything's all moving at the same time.
How does all that move and stay together?
Could it just fly apart?
Do you anticipate that happening, something happening now?
Well, I think.
I don't know if we're going to be running out and doing a building like that.
It would be exciting if we would.
But the reason we are even looking at doing that is that the Shell Oil Company was looking for a million square feet of space.
And it wasn't available if they were to move and go into another building.
And if we could have got the Shell Oil Company to have agreed to enter into an agreement with us, that would have given us the basis to build that building.
a multi-million dollar development like that, you have to have a major tenant in there to...
It's not built on spec.
No, you go bankrupt overnight trying to do something like that.
So we were moving along pretty well, but then the MCORP was in bankruptcy, and the bankruptcy court judge said that they couldn't sell the site to us.
although they had agreed to sell it to us, and said that there had to be an auction to let any developer come in who wanted to to buy that site in competition with us.
Mr. Mitchell decided then that he would withdraw his offer to buy it.
And one of the other problems is that we were moving quickly trying to
you know, get the designs done, try to secure financing.
Our treasurer, George Lake, was working with people in New York, and I think he had engaged Goldman Sachs to try to then raise the funds to finance the project.
Well, we were just getting underway with that when the judge said, oh, no, you're going to have to have this auction.
And we said, well, you know, we're not ready.
No, you're going to have the auction.
So Mr. Mitchell decided to withdraw our offer to buy it, let them go have the auction.
They had the auction, and no one bid.
Does that put you back in?
Well, the site's still there, but also at the same time, the Shell Oil Company decided to work with the Heinz Company, who are the managers of the building that they're in,
to remodel their space to suit their requirements and to stay there, which may have been part of their strategy all along.
One other thing.
We asked you, how does the transportation element of the infrastructure of the woodlands affect your planning, designing?
How has that?
How does it?
Our planning department has the prime responsibility for doing the overall general plan and then maintaining the planning, working with the commercial and residential divisions for their areas.
They employ consultants who do traffic planning, traffic analysis.
They'll study the present population at the Woodlands, what the growth patterns are, and then they'll say from there,
You need this road, this road, this road, this road is what you need if you want to do that kind of development.
If you don't do that, you can do this, this, and this.
So they'll then come in and give us options.
We'll then go through a lot of discussion and thinking about it and say, OK, we're going to do this, this, and this.
And then that kind of lays the bare bones framework for what we will develop.
In other words, if you have a road that's two lanes wide and if you want to have adequate transportation, meaning automobiles, that's not just bumper to bumper.
If you want to have people be able to drive, they have categories of service going from like A to D or E. And probably if you took, you know, if you got on a freeway and you could just drive
65 miles an hour without ever slowing down, that's probably category A.
If you're downtown on the Southwest Freeway at 5 o'clock and you're bumper to bumper, that's probably category D or E. So there's that range of service.
That's how they talk about it.
So if you want to have, say, category C or B, and if it's a two-lane road, then you can do, let's say...
you can do a million square feet, let's say, in this area.
All right?
If you put a four-lane road in there and you want to have the same category of service, then maybe you can do three million square feet.
You want to put a six-lane road in there so it goes like that.
And then it determines are you having surface connections?
Are you going to have overpasses?
Then, of course, you get into the consequences of the cost of that and things like that.

The traffic planning is very much welded into the whole planning process because we have to not only plan the roads for the service of these areas, but we have to lay out the roads so that we have developable parcels of land.
You don't want to have a lot of odd shapes and pieces because you can't build in them very well or no one will want to buy it.
Normally, they want a nice regular piece of land that has certain dimensions to it to make the thing work.
And we generally know that if you have, say, 250 feet from here to here, that generally satisfies most buyers' requirements as to what they might want to do.
So traffic planning is very important.
Most of our traffic, well, all of our traffic planning is surface roads.
The planning department has been working for years on a concept of trying to have a...
like a shuttle bus system that would run east and west through the woodlands, and primarily in what we call this town center area.
And they had carried the plans to quite a stage, and I think they were going to make an application to the Department of Transportation, but I don't think it ever went through.
Any rail talk at all, ever?
Well, no.
I think that Spine...
transit system they were talking about.
At one time, they thought it might be light rail, but I think that they really felt that the cost of that would be prohibitive.
And I think that they were thinking that it would be a spine, all right, going right through, but it would probably be like a bus system, shuttle bus system.
Or maybe all of a sudden, or helicopter pad type things, feasible as transportation devices?
We've had helicopter pads since we opened.
When we opened the Woodlands, we created a pad site right south of here where Woodlands Parkway.
See, Woodlands Parkway in the future is going to go over Groves Mill Road like so.
Well, right now we come up like that and we stop and we take the feeder road going across.
So we create a landing pad for helicopters.
It's used quite regularly.
It's not a commercial pad.
It's not a heliport, but it is a landing pad.
And then we created another one.
over by the first golf course, but I don't think that one ever got used.
What about the medical center?
I don't think a medical, wait a minute, let's think.
We've got a garage there.
I can't remember if we have a pad on top of the garage of that medical center or not.
You've got the ambulance entries on the top level of the garage.
I can't remember if we have a helicopter pad in there or not.
I know one thing I would ask you about is the university.
Where is that going?
Well, that was bad timing.
As I said, I had, when I was with the University of Houston, had got the agreement all resolved for the donation of 400 acres of land, really prime land, to the University of Houston.
The coordinating board are the ones who really started this.
the coordinating board became the ones who were against it.
And if you listen to the coordinating board, he's still there.
He was like director of facilities in those days.
I think he's still head of it, or has he left?
Not Gordon Flack.
Ashworth.
Ken Ashworth.
Ken Ashworth was director of facilities when I was at the University of Houston.
He went and got his doctorate when he was working there at UT.
and then came back to be the commissioner.
Gordon Flack, I think, who is now retired.
I don't know if you know those people.
I don't know Ashworth.
I don't know Flack.
But I think when Ashworth came in, looking at it from his viewpoint, he saw that universities and colleges were getting established around Texas for political reasons.
in many cases, weren't really justified in terms of the population and enrollment served, like, say, Permian Basin, for example.
You take a look at that whole area.

I mean, I was very much into taking a look at population growth, enrollment trends, and all this, because the University of Houston really was using its facilities much better than any other institution in the state.
I mean, of course, people at A&M and UT would like to hear that, or they wouldn't agree with it.
But I know that they were.
because they were being intensely used because they didn't have the space that UT and AM had.

And you know when most professors like to teach, and then you get into the, I can't remember the terms we used, but it really dealt with percent of occupancy and classroom utilization and all that stuff.
I can't even remember the terms anymore, but I remember we got into all those studies.
and how I was trying to advocate that if we could get all the professors to start at 8 o'clock and quit at 6, we could even do better.
Of course, that went about like that in the academic sense.
But, you know, but like, well, I don't want to get into a lot of stuff, but there were institutions that had been approved in state legislatures that had never been approved for political reasons.
And I think the...
The Victoria campus, University of Houston, was one that I don't think should have ever...
I was in that initial meeting when those people came and talked to us.
University of Houston didn't go out for that.
They came to us.
Or came to the University of Houston and said, we want to get this.
And I think maybe A&M didn't want to do it or something.
I don't think A&M wanted to do that.
In fact, when University of Houston...
I was told by Pat Nicholson, who was there during all those...
period when they were trying to get the University of Houston to become a state-supported.
The University of Houston had gone to the University of Texas.
And I don't know if they ever gone to A&M and said, we'd like to be a part of your system.
Well, I didn't know that.
And they said no.
Nowadays, I mean, in the last 20 years, they would have loved to have that.
Oh, yeah.
A&M would have loved to have it too.
Oh, yeah.
But A&M had dropped Arlington and everything they could for a while.
Well, as you probably know, there was a lot of politics and a lot of decisions that were made, like the downtown college that the university required.
That was political, too.
But anyway, so back to that story.
I think Ashworth rightfully saw that a lot of that was happening and that it was costing the state of Texas a lot of money to support, maintain, continue this.
They've got to put a lid on this and stop this proliferation of colleges and universities throughout the state, try to get some handle on how the state's going to develop.
Now, California had, I think, an excellent system.
There may be prejudice coming from California, but they had the University of California, and that took the top, I think, 12.5% of the
high school enrollment.
Then they had the state college system that took a top 33%.
And then any student graduated from high school could go to the community college system.
They had an excellent community college system.
Maybe 200 community colleges.
And it was free.
You went free to community college.
And if you can make it there, then you could apply to either go to a state college or to the university.
There's one university.
University of California, and then the state colleges, which, of course, the state colleges never liked to be called state colleges.
They later became called state universities.
But I knew that system well.
The state government had adopted the plan.
State Department of Finance went along.
State University of California had done a restudy of population back in the 50s or so.
And that's what laid out the whole plan for the Development University of California, which then recommended the establishment
of the major campuses of the university, and to establish one at Santa Cruz, San Diego, Irvine.
There was an excellent system.
Texas never had a plan like that.
And it's been a free-for-all scramble.
All that stuff is really out there.
It's just not been .
But that's what the coordinating board has been trying to do.
I mean, in the good old days, anybody want to start a new department of history, go start a department of history.
Gottlieb this morning, though, said
or see if I remember this right, it was his impression that had Mr. Mitchell gone with either UT or A&M.
Could have had it.
Oh, yeah.
Because you probably know Mr. Mitchell is a graduate of A&M, been a great supporter of A&M.
But he's always felt the University of Houston really serves the Houston community.
despite what UT and A&M think, provide pretty good education for people who cannot afford to go to A&M and UT, and has done an excellent job.
He felt that a campus here should be related to the University of Houston system as such, rather than A&M.
He felt strong about it, and that was it.
He's had friends of his who said to him, George, you've got an excellent idea, but you've got the wrong university.
And I'm sure he's been said, if you go A&M or UT, you'll get it.
So anyway, back to your question.

We got the 400 acres, donated to University of Houston about this time, coordinating board afterwards, restudying the whole, even though they said you should expand, start to look back maybe seven or eight years later and saying, well, things are really ongoing.
This is really a mess.
We've got to get some organization here.
We can't let people start new camps because it costs the state a lot of money.
And so they put a clamp on it.
Dr. Hoffman went to the coordinating board to make a petition to try to get them to approve it.

People from the Huntsville area, Sam Houston and that, were fighting politically to fight against it because they thought that that would seriously affect the enrollment at Sam Houston State University.
Got the support of one of their local
state legislators to come and argue against it.
And it didn't get approved, and that was really the last big opportunity to get through.
There had been other attempts after that time, but never struck.
The land is still there, and Houston still has it?
No, the land is gone now.
It's been used for other purposes.
So you really don't anticipate that it's going to happen?
I don't anticipate it coming and happening.
If it does, it'll be a long time from now.
That's unfortunate, because I think Mr. Mitchell's
correct, that would be an integral element in the development of the community.
Oh, it would have been wonderful.
Yeah, we had the area all planned.
It was on the other side of Lake Woodlands.
He felt that this would give an opportunity for students in Montgomery County, because there isn't anything beyond the 12th grade here.
And also, it would be a state-supported institution.
So, I mean, the concept was great.
The timing politically
mean politically in terms of the state and everything was just unfortunate.
And maybe if, you know, maybe if Dr. Hoffman had, maybe if he had had the opportunity to line up political forces himself, it may have happened.
But there are too many other, you know, jealousies and territorial things going along that were working against it by that time.
That's my view of the thing.
So anyway, the Woodlands lost having a campus at the University of Houston.
We tried to create a center here.
And we had it in a building up the road here to try to get something started by offering courses.
But that became real hard to try to get professors to come from the University of Houston and come here and do that.
And that's about when David Gottlieb got involved, because he got involved in this little center that we were starting.
Well, we're about to run out of your time, but would you wrap us up?
I know a while ago you said that you see great times ahead for the woodlands in terms of population growth.
Yeah, well, in terms of our commercial development.
Do you think that kind of expansion that you anticipate will change the complexion, the environment in the woodlands?
Do you anticipate much change?
It'll change the appearance of this whole town center area as it develops towards the mall and around the mall with things like this.
It's going to make a big change.
But I think the change is going to be one of quality.
And while it'll introduce a more urban character, I think it's going to be a splendid contrast between what we have now and what we have there.
And I think this will then start to give more of a focus of a downtown compared to what we have now
You know, we've got a group of buildings here and some buildings here, but there's no focus to the area.
And I think this will give some real center, real focus to this commercial town center development.
And so I would see that in the future, we're going to have larger buildings, you know, 10, 20-story buildings in height.
Now, of course, this is predicated on, hopefully, some slow to moderate growth and improvement of the economy of the Houston area.
That would be a major centerpiece.
That would be a major centerpiece.
Plus, this is really a big window from I-45 into the woodlands.
Right now, you go by, it's all trees along here.
You don't know anything is here.
That's an interesting point.
That's something that has always struck me about the woodlands is it was a mystery.
Yeah, that's right.
We say to ourselves, that was really dumb of us.
We should have got right down here in the beginning and started this development.
We said, well, other people said, well, we ought to start over the center and work backwards.
It's like the dumbbell theory of development, where you own this piece of land, and you develop this and develop this.
You do that because this becomes more valuable, because you create the market forces.
So we've had arguments back and forth.
I mean, this mall, when Pereira designed it, was a way over here.
And then it's been here and here.
Well, anyway, now it's here.
And so if that happens, we can say, well, we've got this Pinecroft development that's going to take place right here.
And we've already started the land development for a large Target store.
It's going to go up here because this is here.
So you can see things are going to start happening.
And this will be a gorgeous development to drive here.
This is going to be about a 25-acre lake.
Looking right across here, there's going to be a hotel here.

office building here we're going to have a civic building there this will be our first phase of this development with three office buildings around a very large parking structure looking onto this water it'll be a beautiful development well the details are nicely done yeah there's a sense of we put a lot of effort into the planning
of what we do and the design.
And there's a lot of people participate.
We all have our areas of responsibility, but there's a lot of input coming from different groups.
So we put a lot of thought into it, and I think the result is that we get good quality.
And I think people, as you come around, you can see the quality right down to the signs and the roads and the landscaping and how we deal with the natural environment and everything.
All right, sir.
We thank you very much.
OK.
